  "issue_number": 45,
  "issue_title": "bug: agent can self-approve its own proposals \u2014 forbidden_self_approval gate not implemented",
  "issue_body": "**Description**\n\nThe docs state that by default a proposal cannot be approved by the same actor that filed it. In practice, `kb_approve` in `src/vouch/server.py` passes `_agent()` as `approved_by`, and `proposed_by` on every proposal is also `_agent()` \u2014 the same env var. There is no check anywhere in `proposals.approve()` that compares the two. Any agent can therefore propose and immediately approve its own claims with no human in the loop, defeating the core \"writes require approval\" guarantee described in the README.\n\n`rg \"forbidden_self_approval|approver_role\"` returns nothing in `src/` and `tests/`.\n\n**Steps to Reproduce**\n\n1. Set `VOUCH_AGENT=alice`\n2. Propose a claim via `kb_propose_claim`\n3. Call `kb_approve` with the same agent\n4. Observe: claim is approved and written to `claims/` with `approved_by=\"alice\"` and `proposed_by=\"alice\"` \u2014 no error raised\n\n**Actual Behavior**\n\nThe claim is approved silently. The review gate is completely bypassed.\n\n**Expected Behavior**\n\n`proposals.approve()` should raise `ProposalError(\"forbidden_self_approval\")` when `approved_by == proposal.proposed_by`, unless the config sets `review.approver_role` to `\"trusted-agent\"` to explicitly opt out.\n\n**Environment**\n\n- Python 3.11+\n- vouch pre-1.0",
  "merged_at": "2026-05-25T07:47:36.000Z",
